          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During a mediolateral episiotomy, which two muscles of the superficial perineal </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During a mediolateral episiotomy, which two muscles of the superficial perineal pouch are divided?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ischiocavernosus and deep transverse perinei</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Ischiocavernosus covers the crus and lies lateral to the incision line; deep transverse perinei is in the deep pouch, not the superficial pouch.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bulbospongiosus and superficial transverse perinei</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These two superficial pouch muscles lie directly in the path of a mediolateral episiotomy, which angles away from the anal sphincter.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>External anal sphincter and bulbospongiosus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The mediolateral incision is specifically designed to avoid the external anal sphincter; cutting it would cause faecal incontinence.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Levator ani and ischiocavernosus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Levator ani forms the pelvic diaphragm above the perineal pouches and is not in the path of a perineal incision.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The mediolateral incision specifically cuts through the bulbospongiosus and superficial transverse perinei — both lie in the superficial pouch and in the direct path of the incision."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The mediolateral episiotomy divides the bulbospongiosus and superficial transverse perinei, both contents of the superficial perineal pouch."
                }
              ],
