          "label": "<p>According to Goodsall's rule, when the external opening of a fistula-in-ano lies</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>According to Goodsall's rule, when the external opening of a fistula-in-ano lies posterior to the transverse anal line, the fistulous track:</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Runs in a straight radial line to the nearest point on the dentate line</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A straight radial track is predicted when the external opening lies anterior to the transverse anal line, not posterior.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Curves to open at the posterior midline (six o'clock) of the anal canal</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Goodsall's rule states that posterior external openings follow a curved track to the posterior midline of the dentate line — a key guide for surgical planning.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spirals above the puborectalis to form a suprasphincteric track</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Suprasphincteric fistulae are a Parks' classification category based on sphincter relationship, not a course predicted by Goodsall's rule.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bypasses both sphincters and opens into the rectum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes an extrasphincteric fistula in Parks' classification, often associated with Crohn's disease — not a track course predicted by Goodsall's rule.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Goodsall's rule: anterior openings have a straight track to the dentate line; posterior openings curve to the posterior midline (six o'clock position)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Posterior external openings follow a curved track to the six o'clock position — Goodsall's rule is essential for planning fistula exploration."
                }
              ],
